text:
he sat beside me above the waters last spring and told me,"you know, for a change, you should try loving yourself." and i laughed really hard at him. he looked me in the eye and i asked him,"what does that mean? there is something sacred about the love you recieve from your beloved." he looked at me, the sunlight touched his tired eyes, drawing wrinkles around the corners. he let out a little smile, i could see one of his crooked teeth between his lips, and he looked away. he holds my hand more firmly, and lets out a sigh. and i recognise that sigh, the one filled with sorrow and loss. he looks back at me and says, "all that time i kept chasing love in my youth, just like you, and nothing fulfilled me, all the love i gave or got. and i realised nothing gives you more happiness than working on yourself, and solitude gave me that opportunity." i never understood what he meant, until the last few months. loving yourself seems so ordinary, that's why we find ourselves clueless when it comes to that. it's maintaining boundaries you once erased because you gave into the person you thought was home. it's giving yourself the liberty to make mistakes, eat the sugary snack you've been craving, go for a run, or just waste time alone, by yourself. it's knowing you owe yourself the same time and care you so easily give away, and also knowing people will point fingers at you once you make them feel a little less entitled, once you remove them from that throne, they will label you selfish, but self love will teach you to be okay with that. you deserve space. you deserve time. and the person you deserve it from the most is, definitely, you.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
"if power mainly resides with men, what does this imply for accountability? if the world is unfair, who is responsible for making it right? this cannot be a burden just for women. we men must play an active role in ensuring a more just world. we men must not only be part of gender equality, not just a conversation, but the solution. we men must defy the structures of patriarchy and the outdated notions of manhood and use that questioning to build more justice societies."
_
powerful speech by @winstoncduke at the @heforshe impact summit, @unitednations

text:
good morning everyone! how are you? it's been a while. i'm doing well. i'm in saigon still. i'm working on my book and health. i'm feeling great and honestly better than i have in probably 6 years. good things are happening. 
as many of you know, i have been through a lot in my life. a lot of it i share openly but somethings i still can't, and that's why i decided to write a book about my life. in the process of writing over the last few months, i have garnered a sense of peace that i have never experienced. in the process of writing, i have laughed, cried, been angry, felt helpless, and wanted to scream at the world. i've also felt empowered, brave, secure, and capable.  many of these emotions i haven't felt so viscerally in my life. 
it dawned on me that like in my youth writing is one of the most cathartic things for me. as an adult and a survivor of horrific trauma, some self-inflicted but most of it at the hands of adults, it hit me like a brick that writing is still a compelling mechanism for me. 
as i sat up watching the red sunrise a couple of weeks ago in thailand, it hit me that i wanted to give other people the same outlet that i have been utilizing and i came up with @traumaletters

www.traumaletters.com is a site that i built that is for anonymous creative letter writing for anything including but not limited to trauma around child abuse, sexual abuse, domestic violence, sex, drugs, addiction, and suicide. the letters are both good and evil and there is no wrong or right. the site is only a week old, but i don't believe in waiting for things to be perfect before sharing them with the world. that said, i hope that you will check out #traumaletters share it on your page, and maybe even submit your own anonymous letter. i also welcome any thoughts or suggestions that you have as this is not about me and i want this to be a platform utilized by anyone that needs it. so if you have ideas, please message me.

i also want to take a moment and say thank you to everyone who has ever had my back. i am so lucky to have friends like you, and i am appreciative of you. 
have an amazing day and remember that you can do anything.

www.traumaletters.com is a site that i built that is for anonymous creative letter writing for anything including but not limited to trauma around child abuse, sexual abuse, domestic violence, sex, drugs, addiction, and suicide. the letters are both good and evil and there is no wrong or right. the site is only a week old, but i do not believe in waiting for things to be perfect before sharing them with the world. that said, i hope that you will check out #traumaletters share it on your page, and maybe even submit your own anonymous letter. i also welcome any thoughts or suggestions that you have as this is not about me and i want this to be a platform utilized by anyone that needs it. so if you have ideas, please message me.

i also want to take a moment and say thank you to everyone who has ever had my back. i am so lucky to have friends like you, and i am appreciative of you. 
have an amazing day and remember that you can do anything.

text:
"beauty to me" Â when i was younger i used to think my beauty was measured by the neatness of my hair, the colour of my eyes, the colour of my nails, having the least amount of noticed pores on my face, and my hip to bust ratio. *

i was taught, that my beauty was measured by the amount of melanin in my skin, the elasticity and length of my curls, my height in heels. the amount of jewelry i wore, the quality of my clothing. the amount of curse words i used, the way i crossed my legs when i sat. my legs in a skirt, and of course my hip to bust ratio. *

today i know beauty is immeasurable, and beauty is as simple as a genuine smile, or the glisten of eyes caught in the sunlight. the crazed eyes caused from passion and the feeling i evoke in the people around me. *

photography by: @moemaureen

-

"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.

text:
refuse to be silenced
__________________
if youâ€™ve been around me, chances are you know that i have a lot of strong opinions  that often go against the â€˜crowdâ€™. and iâ€™m not afraid to passionately share what i think. that comes from experience, regret, success and having strong women in my life. it also comes from the fact that for too long, women have been told to be quiet. many of our girls have been told that in order to get a man, you have to be quiet, soft, agreeable and keep your opinions to yourself. that messaging unfortunately translates to girls not feeling their voice or opinions are valued, and so they are silent when itâ€™s time to speak up in class, they are silent when they need to communicate with their parents and too often, they are silent, when they are victims of sexual harassment or assault. and in many ways society is still telling women to be quiet... when it comes to our bodies or our stories of harassment and abuse. that is why i applaud #metoo and #timesup and the womenâ€™s marches, because it is time that we have a stronger voice in the conversations that matter and that our voice be respected. 
so if you are like me... strong, outspoken and opinionated... donâ€™t worry about dimming your light to be more attractive or likable. like yourself. love yourself. be yourself. and while you are at, let them know that you are here. 
now go on and have yourself a great day! ğŸ˜˜
#mindfulmonday

text:
an act of courage is most likely identified as such after the act, when the dust settles and you have time to think about it in the larger context. at the moment the decision is simply to act or not. such was my experience about 10 years ago when some folks asked me to help a black woman who had been stopped for speeding on her way home from her nursing assistant's job. the incident escalated and resulted in her being arrested on several felonies, the facts of which seemed unjustified. 
over the next year i led a group of white and black, male and female, community members to challenge law enforcement's "blue wall" protecting the office, to show up at court hearings, hold rallies, to stand on the steps of prescott's courthouse to show support and seek justice for her.  a jury found her guilty, but the judge, we think, saw the problem for what it was and gave her no jail time and unsupervised probation.

today she is a successful nurse, but it took years for her to get her rights back and her record completely cleared as though the nightmare never happened. getting involved in such a case had its risks for all of us in a state with little diversity tolerance. it was a great example that when we stand together for justice, we win. ***submit your story of courage here: http://illuminatefilmfestival.com/acts-of-courage-form 
#1000actsofcourage
#thischangeseverything
#illuminatefilmfestival

#blacklivesmatter #womensreality #metoo #everydaysexism #fem2 #feminism #feminist #actofcourage

1ï¸âƒ£ both men and women can be harassed.
2ï¸âƒ£ illegal sexual harassment can occur between people of the same sex.
3ï¸âƒ£ sexual harassment can occur outside of the workplace if behavior happens at a work-related event.
4ï¸âƒ£ supervisors or those in authority positions are not the only ones who can be harassers. you can be harassed by a coworker and, in some cases, a third party such as an agent or client of your employer.

text: law school is extremely triggering (reference to se/ual a/sau/t) you will have to defend people you donâ€™t particularly agree with. you have no choice really (in general). every week we are given a few scenarios to prepare for. this week we are told to defend a mr michael oakley who went clubbing and grabbed a womanâ€™s breasts aka sexually assaulted her. now here i am; an advocate for human rights (yes i am aware everyone has a right to fair trail and having a barrister helps with fair hearings) and someone who speaks up against sexual assault almost every single second of my life, and iâ€™m placed in a position where iâ€™m trying to figure out a way to argue that my client reasonably believed mrs dawson had consented to being touched in that way! so kids- it is upon you (defendant) to determine whether the victim has consented or not. ask her/him/them if they are consenting. it will protect people from being sexually violated, it will protect you from litigation and it will avoid us lawyers the pain and emotional/mental anguish of trying to defend you and it will certainly help keep our anxiety at bay. ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€âš–ï¸ ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€âš–ï¸ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€âš–ï¸ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€âš–ï¸ğŸ‘©ğŸ»â€âš–ï¸#lawschool #barstudent #sexualassault #metoo #consent #criminallaw #criminallawyers #nomeansno #lawblogger #thisisnotconsent

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: today we honor tarana burke, a civil rights activist and founder of the #metoo movement. tarana burke grew up in the bronx, new york and graduated from aurburn university. she founded the "just be" non-profit focused on the wellness of black girls in alabama and created the #metoo movement in 2006 to raise awareness of the pervasiveness of sexual assault or abuse. this movement gained a larger following in 2017 after the harvey weinstein sexual abuse allegations. tarana burke is currently the senior director at girls for gender equity in brooklyn. #genderresoucesccny #cuny #ccny #blackhistorymonth #metoo

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies. 
they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
#bali has had already hundreds (or thousands) issues with women being chased, sexually harassed, insulted physically and emotionally. some of my girlfriends had this issue twice, no matter if it happened on their way home from dinner or even during the day while jogging on the streets.

of course, all of the women directly contacted the police and local administration (banjar), unfortunately, they donâ€™t want to do anything about it and always find an excuse to blame the women themselves.

weâ€™ve had enough, bali is amazing and all of us consider it as our home, we want it to be safe.

weâ€™ve kept the silence but this snowball has to start moving. right now a team of girls working on spreading the word in public media, our goal is to wake up the minds of bali government, especially in #canggu, so they can finally do some actions to protect their tourists and make their paradise safe again.

dear friends, please help us to sign this petition (link on my profile) and spread the word, we canâ€™t sit and look at this anymore! @makerswomen 
#safetyinbali #balibesafe #womenharassment #womensafety #indonesiantourism #balitourism #canggu #internationalsafety #canggu #bali #metoo #stopsexualassault #makebalisafe #wedeservebetter #itsneverokay #pleasestop #makerswoman #stopsexualharassment #balilife #balidaily #guguide

the stats are 1:3 women have been sexually assaulted/abused and 1:5 boys. the 
as a trauma specialist, i can say that itâ€™s more then that...itâ€™s about 75% of the population that has experienced either overt or covert abuse. children deserve better.
be the adult who does better.
#bethechange #endtraumacycles #epigenetics #acestudy 
remember 
that underneath a defensive exterior is a wound itâ€™s protecting..
that the presentation is a cover for what couldnâ€™t be expressed with safety...
that sex most often isnâ€™t even about sex...
that struggles are about unearthing the deep seeded root of something seeking the light.
truth does set you free...

we appreciate all the actors who showed up to do this movie.

text:
â€œi used a wood to kill her after several warnings for her to desist from taking calls from men in my house. i have been suspecting that my wife was sleeping around with other men in my village but in the heat of argument, i killed her. my late wife brought men into our matrimonial home and my culture abhors such an act; that was why i killed her to save the family from the shame,â€ -these are the words of 32-year-old jibrin abu. .
according to naijadiary.ng abu who hails from dabogi village in lapai, was arrested by the niger state police in nigeria for allegedly beating his wife, victoria, to death with a piece of wood over allegations that she cheated on him. .
reports confirm that abu, after killing his wife, attempted to commit suicide by drinking "sniper" insecticide, but his attempt failed as he was rushed to the lapai general hospital by police operatives and was treated. .
he is said to be tried in court soon.
.

however, the necessity of creating tangible change and providing real support to people affected by these issues can not be overlooked.

text:
mariam goes to school.

2 weeks ago, during our vocational and skills training session in oke ira, badore, mariam's mother told the team that out of 6 children, only her boys (3 of them) go to school. the girls do not go to school because her family can't afford to send all of them, so her husband decided that only the males will go to school.

today we have enrolled one of the girls (mariam) to school. unfortunately, her sisters are in their late teens and they won't be able to cope but mariam is 5 years old.

mariam wore her new uniform and screamed excitedly and she is full of thanks.

this isn't going to be an easy journey for mariam. mariam is older than her classmates, she doesn't understand a word in english or yoruba, she can't identify figures or numbers but it will be worth it.

that girl is a fighter.

#education #educateher #metoo #womenempowerment #empowerment #sdg5 #sdg4

aviation: precious minutes will pass (7/10) by nicholas jones, 10 january 2018. -

i know that youâ€™ve been asking where iâ€™ve been,
and here is the honest truth,
that i canâ€™t come over for the sake of myself,
because i donâ€™t want to hurt you,

precious minutes will pass between,
whenever i first get there - and whenever i eventually leave,
then youâ€™ll ask me to stay,
with your heart on your sleeve and i just wonâ€™t know what to do,

because the part of me that loves you,
is the part of me that has to live without you. -

now go on and have yourself a great day! ğŸ˜˜

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
christopher wylie, who worked with a cambridge university academic to obtain the data, told the observer: â€œwe exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles. and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.â€ documents seen by the observer, and confirmed by a facebook statement, show that by late 2015 the company had found out that information had been harvested on an unprecedented scale. however, at the time it failed to alert users and took only limited steps to recover and secure the private information of more than 50 million individuals.

the data was collected through an app called thisisyourdigitallife, built by academic aleksandr kogan, separately from his work at cambridge university. through his company global science research (gsr), in collaboration with cambridge analytica, hundreds of thousands of users were paid to take a personality test and agreed to have their data collected for academic use.

however, the app also collected the information of the test-takersâ€™ facebook friends, leading to the accumulation of a data pool tens of millions-strong. facebookâ€™s â€œplatform policyâ€ allowed only collection of friendsâ€™ data to improve user experience in the app and barred it being sold on or used for advertising. the discovery of the unprecedented data harvesting, and the use to which it was put, raises urgent new questions about facebookâ€™s role in targeting voters in the us presidential election. it comes only weeks after indictments of 13 russians by the special counsel robert mueller which stated they had used the platform to perpetrate â€œinformation warfareâ€ against the us.

carole cadwalladr & emma graham-harrison
the guardian

text:
i wanted to make this drawing about few months ago and i finally did. based on my experience hooking up with a possibly narcissist, and in this drawing i illustrate what is being in a relationship with one. a relationship full of lies, deceit, betrayals, pain, abuse, manipulation, confusion etc, even thought, at the beginning everything seems perfect and unreal, like, "too perfect to be truth". you feel sick, anxious, fear, depresed, confused, madness, weak, tired...also you get to feel like the biggest fool in the world for all the shit you did just to keep that person happy, a person who never cared about you in first place, a person who never existed either, a person that only wants to feed from you meanwhile you are getting weaker every second you are with them. so now, i made this drawing to close definitely this chapter of my life, let it completly go and do not touch the subject ever again, and better focus on myself and heal from all this mess, at least it didn't got "too far" , so i can heal more quickly, but i kinda feel guilty and dirty . my advice is, be sure to meet very well that person before starting a relationship, love yourself cuz if not, you will only bring tÃ³xic relationship to your life and you deserve more than that, you deserve better, not a person that treats you like a piece of shit. also be alert to the red flags, so you can leave on time and save yourlsef. love y'allğŸ’• . ~song: distant traces of beauty - ace attorney ost

text:
hi friends! i am so excited to introduce clara wisner of @revolutionarylifestyle to you. remember back in january when you voted on which webinar topic you wanted to hear? well clara will be talking about trauma & body image on march 5 at 6pm mst.

in this webinar nutritionist and psychotherapist clara wisner will be exploring the relationship between physical and emotional trauma and negative body image. from disordered eating to body dysmorphia, experiencing trauma is a factor in how we heal and get to a place of food freedom and body peace. 
in this webinar you will learn: 
1. 5 steps to stop hating your body right now.
2. how past trauma or abuse contributes to body image issues + disordered eating.
3. the 3 best tools to use daily to love yourself more and feel more comfortable in your body.

we can't wait to  see you there! please register for this webinar. ğŸ‘‰ link in bio. dm me with any questions you have.

#weareher #revolutionarylifestyle #trauma #bodyimage #bodypositive #survivorsisters #toxicrelationships #heal #empower #restore #webinar #metoo #nomore #loveyourself #bodypositivity

text:
"collective action and shared responsibility for driving gender parity is what makes international women's day successful"

did you know?
"international women's day (march ğŸ˜ is a global day celebrating the social, economic, cultural and political achievements of women. the day also marks a call to action for accelerating gender parity. international women's day (iwd) has occurred for well over a century, with the first march 8 iwd gathering supported by over a million people in austria, denmark, germany and switzerland. prior to this the socialist party of america, united kingdom's suffragists and suffragettes, and further groups campaigned for women equality. today, iwd belongs to all groups collectively everywhere. iwd is not country, group or organisation specific. make iwd your day! - everyday!

text:
i really loved #christine armstrongâ€™s brilliantly honest article in the @thestmagazine yesterday about the growing elephant in the office that is workplace resentment between the sexes..... .
it really echoes a lot of what iâ€™ve been hearing from my local flexible working community over the last couple of months. .
flexible working is a work pattern that employers are prepared to consider - itâ€™s been reported that 68% of mums make a request for at least one type for flexible working practice, and in the majority they are approved.  great stats right?  not entirely......
.

most employers know that flexible working encourages business benefits including staff retention and motivation but what they really are still not getting right is the culture needed for flexible working to work.
.
the article yesterday quoted some pretty depressing stats around this; -18% is the percentage by which working mothers are more stressed than other people. -21% fewer woman work in full-time executive roles at ftse250 firms in 2018 than in 2017. -one of the most alarming stats quoted was that 16% of male managers hesitate to mentor a woman - this is three times higher than before the #metoo movement ğŸ™€
.

something needs to change and change quickly to ensure that the resentment gap doesnâ€™t grow any wider..... there needs to be open, honest conversations within the workplace and a shift away from flexible working being only a â€˜female thingâ€™. only when everyone involved starts being honest about life reality can it really be a success ğŸ‘ŠğŸ»
.

text:
churches, please read and heed these wise words from al mohler's response to the houston chronicle's #scbtoo report (pictured: https://albertmohler.com/2019/02/11/reality-sexual-abuse-hits-home-happened-now/).â €
.â €
they justify concerns expressed by rachael denhollander in response to sgc: â €
"in their response, sgc claims that no third-party independent review is necessary because, among other things, covenant life church (clc) commissioned an independent investigation into how matters were handled. while the sgc statement simply describes clc as â€œa church that was then part of sovereign grace,â€ clc was in fact the flagship church of the denomination. furthermore, cj mahaney was the lead pastor at the time nearly all the alleged mishandlings of abuse at clc took place, including the abuses perpetrated by nathaniel morales. because the sgc statement relies heavily on the conclusions of this independent review, it bears further scrutiny here. there are several aspects which ought to have been disclosed, related to this review. ...â €
.â €
"in short, the firm and investigators had none of the expertise normally required of any team charged with handling such an investigation. the firm used poor methodology. they chose not to speak with key witnesses, including those who had raised the allegations, and were not allowed to speak with others key witnesses, including leaders at sgm. further, as discussed below, they did not disclose key evidence and blatantly misrepresented additional key evidence. finally, they used attorney-client privilege as a shield against public accountability and refused to disclose evidence or even the final written report - save for an oral retelling of the report to the members of clc. (i have transcripts of this report and access to the audio recording, which was provided to me by survivors.)"â €
.â €
read her full statement: https://www.facebook.com/notes/rachael-denhollander/response-to-sovereign-grace-churches/1720170721396574/â €
.â €

6 weeks pregnant signed off with stress, 3 kids, mortgage and faced with a compromise agreement or fight a corporates legal team. that 2003 and itâ€™s still happening please see @pregnant_then_screwed call to action #repost @pregnant_then_screwed with @get_repost

the government has launched a consultation into the 3 month time limit to raise a tribunal claim for pregnant women and new mums - we need your help.

this is our chance to shout as loud as we can that women need greater access to justice. the idea that pregnant women and new mums can start a tribunal process within 3 months is utter insanity and it results in 0.6% of victims raising a claim. i was sacked when i was 4 months pregnant and a week later i discovered i was having a high risk pregnancy. the doctor said to me: 'whatever you do, dont get stressed.' the 3 month time limit forced me to choose between the health of my baby and accessing the justice i deserved.

i need you all to send an email to the people at beis so they know how important this is. the more emails they get, the more likely it is they will do something about this. i have even written the email for you so all you have to do is copy and paste. the link is in my bio. please comment below to say you have done it so we have an idea how many emails they get.

if you want to help ignite change, then now is your chance. 
big thanks to @olga.fitzroy for her help with this.
#givemesix #pregnantthenscrewed #metoo #timesup

text:
on april 16, 2017, in the village of shambhupura in banswara, rajasthan, india, kachru, 21, and monica, 19, got married and were cousins but there family, was not fine with it. the couple were paraded naked, beaten, and sexually assaulted by the whole village of shambhupura and family members including their fathers, brothers and, uncles. the accused have been booked for rioting,Â wrongful restraint and confinement, wrongly causing hurt, attempted murder, and sexual harassment.
-
-
"the men and children of the village have fled to some other place due to the fear of arrest.
according to the police, on thursday, varaseng resident varanseng resident lord ratna maida, twenty-four-year-old padla resident shankar son lalji, kundelia resident forgotten wife dhulia, resident of shambhupura, gutu son shyama, subhash son hiraji, kangi son kalu, dilip son chetan, ramatu wife kalu and bhusli wife bheema was arrestedÂ earlier, nine people including the father of the girl were arrested on wednesday."

text:
long before #metoo, female artists were calling out sexual violence | vanderbilt news
#
photo courtesy vivian green frydsocial media has brought sexual assault into the public eye, but bearing witness to sexual violence in popular culture didnâ€™t begin with the invention of tweets and posts, according to vanderbilt art history professor vivien green fryd. â€œwhatâ€™s happening today with the metoo movement is a continuation of the feminist movement of the 1970s,â€ fryd said. â€œit was a time when female artists consciously began using their works to challenge social conceptions and the legal definitions of rape and incest in order to shift the dominant narrative of violence against women.â€ in her new book, against our will: sexual trauma in american art since 1970 (february 2019, penn state university press), fryd chronicles the evolution of this decades-long intervention through the lens of art history. she highlights feminist artists suzanne lacy, leslie labowitz, faith ringgold, judy chicago and kara walker, whose works sought to end the silence surrounding sexual violence. â€œit was a time when women began to use their art to express their own experiences with sexual violence, as well as challenge the male dominated art world,â€ fryd said. artists and art historians also began to more openly confront the works of masters like rubensâ€¦

text:
christopher wylie, the whistleblower who exposed the widespread misuse of data by his former employer, cambridge analytica, has revealed how the company â€œweaponisedâ€ the fashion industry in the run up to the 2016 us election, which he claims helped donald trump get elected.

speaking at the annual bof voices festival in oxfordshire, wylie revealed for the first time a matrix based on data collected by the firm which he claims can show how usersâ€™ preferences for particular brands on social media platforms â€“ facebook, in particular â€“ were then used to help target these same users with pro-trump messaging. he compared the misuse of fashion-based data as one of the campaignâ€™s lesser reported â€œweapons of mass destructionâ€. - they [cambridge analytica] looked at actual people. how they engaged with certain brands was put into a funnel and helped build the algorithms, wylie explained. - when you look at personality traits, music and fashion are the most informative [tools] for predicting someoneâ€™s personality. a userâ€™s predilection for a particular label gives, he said, a very clear indication of what reports often call â€œpopulist political signallingâ€. cambridge analytica, which wasÂ shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
since valentineâ€™s day is coming up this week i thought i would dedicate my posts to the occasion. today, i want to talk about consent. â¤ï¸what is consent? â¤ï¸
â€¢
â€¢
it is a voluntary agreement to engage in sexual activity of any kind, and it must be given freely. therefore, you cannot receive consent from someone who is intoxicated, unconscious or incapable of giving consent. additionally, consent is not freely given when you threaten others as well. remember a no means no. 
further, people can change their minds as well. they may have given consent 20 minutes ago, but maybe 20 minutes later they want to go get burgers instead. this means that they withdrew their consent and are no longer interested in engaging in any type of sexual activity. â€¢
â€¢
i wanted to talk about consent because according to statistics canada sexual assault is one of the most underreported crimes. this has a lot do with shame, guilt and stigma that is associated around it. this can happen to anyone, and it is so important that we are there for each other and supporting one another. movements like #metoo are important because they bring awareness to the issue. in fact, canada found that more people had started reported their sexual assaults to the police after the movement started. if someone is sexually assaulted they are more likely to have post-traumatic stress disorder (ptsd) which can impact many facets of their lives. further, someone who is sexually assaulted are 3 times more likely to have a major depressive episode. therefore, it is important that we provide support to individuals who have gone through sexual assault.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

in this week'sÂ love and hip hop: miami, jessie wooÂ talks about being sexually assaulted and the other women on the show rallied around her in support. in a preview clip from the episode, trina hasÂ taken jessie, joy, and chinese kitty to an event at which #metoo founder tarana burke is speaking. â€œwe spend most of our time trying to forget, but we recognize the pain. that's literally what metoo is â€” it's empowerment with empathy. 
__â€¨in another preview of the episode, jessie confided in trina about her assault. jessie told trina that she was allegedly raped at an industry event. "as a rape victim, you feel like youâ€™re powerless. you feel like youâ€™re a loserâ€“you feel so low. you feel like you donâ€™t matter, she said.
__â€¨in a 2018 cnn article titled â€œback from the brink of suicide, they want to save othersâ€ jessie was interviewed where she discussed being suicidal and knowing that someone loved her and cared about her is what kept her from ending her own life. that someone was her brother jeremy. "he talked me out of it, and that definitely was a turning point for me," said jessie. at the time, about five years ago, "i had dealt with someone raping me." the trauma of the rape, she said, was compounded with seeing that person excel professionally. "i just felt like i didn't want to be here anymore," she said.â€¨â€”â€¨earlier today, jessie tweeted, â€œon this day last summer, my abuser made the news. several women in the industry started coming forward with their stories of sexual assault. i thought i was the only one. iâ€™m happy to say that iâ€™m working with the lapd to help over a dozen other women put him behind bars #metoo. â€œi donâ€™t think iâ€™ll be watching this episode because i still have a lot of healing to do. but prayerfully, my testimony ministers to those of you who need it.â€
__â€¨we are sending hugs to jessie for being so brave to share her story with the world. hopefully, her story will help with her healing and help another victim who is struggling with coming forward. for more information on the meet visit metoomvmt.org.

text:
standing up: a woman who claimed former melbourne lord mayor robert doyle inappropriately touched her at a dinner in 2016 has spoken publicly about it for the first time and is the first woman to make a formal complaint to police over his behaviour as lord mayor.
kharla williams, a real estate marketer who says mr doyle touched her inner thigh repeatedly while seated at the vip table of a dinner for state government agency melbourne health, said she had lost faith in the ability of the city of melbourne and the agency to resolve her complaint and made a statement to victoria police over the weekend.
the police are using the statement as the basis of a possible investigation into mr doyle, who is one of the most high-profile men in australia to fall from grace as a result of the #metoo movement.
â€˜the investigation that i trusted and had absolute faith in â€“ in hindsight i would look back and think blind faith â€“ is asking me, the victim, to be silent and basically go away.â€™ while kharlaâ€™s actions do kick robert doyleâ€™s behaviour while lord mayor into the police/criminal realm for the first time, it remains to be seen what will happen. however, since this story ran in mondayâ€™s @financialreview, former premier and robert doyle friend jeff kennett has already apologised to her for his public criticisms of her complaint. #smallsteps

see bit.ly/kharla ğŸ“· arsineh@arsineh.com

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since day one.

steve bannon left the wh august 2017 and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? 'j-c' church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt, with the goonsquad known as gop, has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are useless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is no way that gop isn't aware of this - after all, cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got as cambridge analytica. pedofiles - i bet - but the way things are bundled sure makes goebbels shiver.

trump plays along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still - the republicans willingly piggybacked this before the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:

in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
not your regular transformation tuesday. but you'll never be able to heel if you don't close old wounds.
on the left i had just turned 13. this photo was a week before my mum died. 
whom i was the full time carer of for years.
i was living with my drug addict sister because id just been released from hospital after my first suicide attempt. my heart had stopped and id gotten so close to that light at the end of my dark life. 
i was defeated, mad, and hurting. ive got visible cuts on my arms. i was anorexic and had a death wish.
id already been raped, physically and emotionally abused, and had no idea by the time i was 25 id have of spent over 1 year combined in psyc wards, scars not even tattoos could hide and 8 suicide attempts under my sad little belt. 
i may not like myself now days, i may still be a very unwell person, some days i sit in the sun and think about how lucky i am, some days you'll find me curld up on the floor crying, taking every single bit left in me not to cut myself, or worse. i may hate my body and appearance, but it's so easy to forget where i came from. 
i was alone for so long, everyone had given up on me because it was too hard. 
but before anyone has a single thought of judgement in their minds about me i want everyone to know. 
i am a badass, i am a survivor, i am doing my absolute best.
and im proud of me, even on the days when no one else is. ğŸ’•

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
why do some leap ahead while others fall behind in our chaotic, connected age? innew power,Â jeremy heimans and henry timms confront the biggest stories of our time--the rise of mega-platforms like facebook and uber; the out-of-nowhere victories of obama and trump; the unexpected emergence of movements like #metoo--and reveal what's really behind them: the rise of "new power." for most of human history, the rules of power were clear: power was something to be seized and then jealously guarded. this "old power" was out of reach for the vast majority of people. but our ubiquitous connectivity makes possible a different kind of power. "new power" is made by many. it is open, participatory, and peer-driven. it works like a current, not a currency--and it is most forceful when it surges. the battle between old and new power is determining who governs us, how we work, and even how we think and feel. Â new powerÂ shines fresh light on the cultural phenomena of our day, from #blacklivesmatter to the ice bucket challenge to airbnb, uncovering the new power forces that made them huge. drawing on examples from business, activism, and pop culture, as well as the study of organizations like lego, nasa, reddit, and ted, heimans and timms explain how to build new power and channel it successfully. they also explore the dark side of these forces: the way isis has co-opted new power to monstrous ends, and the rise of the alt-right's "intensity machine." in an era increasingly shaped by new power, this groundbreaking book offers us a new way to understand the world--and our role in it.

text:
#goodandmad: the revolutionary power of women's anger 
in the year 2018, it seems as if #womensanger has suddenly erupted into the public conversation. but long before pantsuit nation, before the womenâ€™s march, and before the #metoo movement, womenâ€™s anger was not only politically catalyticâ€”but politically problematic. the story of #femalefury and its cultural significance demonstrates the long history of bitter resentment that has enshrouded womenâ€™s slow rise to political power in america, as well as the ways that anger is received when it comes from women as opposed to when it comes from men. 
with eloquence and fervor, rebecca tracks the history of #femaleanger as political fuelâ€”from suffragettes marching on the white house to office workers vacating their buildings after clarence thomas was confirmed to the supreme court. here traister explores womenâ€™s anger at both men and other women; anger between ideological allies and foes; the varied ways anger is perceived based on its owner; as well as the history of caricaturing and delegitimizing female anger; and the way womenâ€™s collective fury has become transformative political fuelâ€”as is most certainly occurring today. she deconstructs societyâ€™s (and the mediaâ€™s) condemnation of female emotion (notably, #rage) and the impact of their resulting repercussions. 
highlighting a double standard perpetuated against women by all sexes, and its disastrous, stultifying effect, traisterâ€™s latest is timely and crucial. it offers a glimpse into the galvanizing force of womenâ€™s collective anger, which, when harnessed, can change history.
publisher: simon & schuster
publication date: october 2, 2018

text:
my story is a lot different than the others, i was not the victim, i was the one who tried to take advantage.
i had been talking to this guy for awhile, we met through mutual friends, and i found myself falling for him, he told me he felt the same.
he had disclosed to me during one of our conversations that he was a virgin, and had only kissed one other girl, i was not a virgin. 
one night when my mom was out i invited him over and we ended up drinking.
we started making out and then went up to my room. 
things got heavy and we were 69ing when i decided i wanted to have sex.
he told me he wasnâ€™t ready, that he was good just doing oral, but i was drunk and coming on fairly aggressive.
i grabbed a condom from the nightstand and told him we were having sex, then i attempted to put it on him.
he went limp and said he had to go. 
we never really spoke again, when i should have at least apologized.
i have lived with that guilt for years.

even more months later we birthed the idea for this amazing art piece to retaliate and for me to take my power back in my most natural form of expression.

text:
i wanna take a minute to talk about hormonal birth control (which opens up a can of worms). it's tempting to pop a pill and cure a problem. take this and don't worry about getting pregnant! but in suppressing your moon cycle, what are you really doing? women are not designed to function like men: the same everyday. god designed us to have a week of blood, a week where we are forced to sit on the earth and be still. but in removing ourselves from the rhythm of nature, the essence of creation, our periods, that is exactly what we are doing. becoming more like men. we see where men are failing, so we have risen up to play roles that traditionally have belonged to them. earning money, being the head of the household, going to battle.
â€§
in mainstream culture, we see focus on wounds of the divine feminine. #metoo movement, destruction of the earth, shaming sexuality. but the divine masculine has suffered and needs healing just as much. the wrongs done to the feminine are a result of the wounded masculine. homes without fathers, a culture that promotes a caricature of masculinity (money, alcohol, women, material things falsely equated with power), too much softness (in the mind, in the body), being shamed for expressing emotion, lack of connection to others (google "incels"). our ancestors went thousands of years bleeding every month. and now we expect to play god, literally stopping our blood, without suffering repurcussions? we are seeing lack of connection to the body, inability to tell who is a compatible genetic partner (google "birth control and divorce"), estrogen from pee that ends up in our drinking water, possible infertility once you stop using the pill...
â€§
my heart goes out to women using bc and not giving it a second thought because they weren't informed. doctors prescribe bc for acne, or because periods are "annoying." periods should be celebrated as a time when the veil between spirit and material worlds is thin. pms is your intuition saying "if it's not a hell yes then it's a hell no." i am not doctor, but i have always believed in addressing the root of a problem, not the symptoms. i am passionate about this and happy to cont the convo ğŸ™ğŸ¼

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
these words have been leaping through my brain since the end of  last year. â€œyou are not a victim for sharing your story...
you are a survivor setting the world on fire with your truth.â€ i had been battling with the decision to speak about other parts of my story. to allow my nakedness of past trauma to flood your squares. but time and again i kept saying nope, iâ€™m not ready. iâ€™m still doing the healing. it wasnâ€™t until this last month that i think after decades of living with trauma and guilt and shame i finally broke free. 
i had been motivated many times to tell my â€œotherâ€ story. in fact iâ€™ve even been pushed by many of you for the last 4 years to go public with what had happened in my life.  especially during the #metoo movement. 
what was happening was i was afraid to give myself permission to speak my truth. iâ€™m in a place now, where i have to give myself the permission to tell you that i went through some pretty severe trauma from being raped at a very young age of 13 years old. then i was raped again in college.  and i lived with it in the dark for almost a decade.  but i know iâ€™m not a victim. and i know that i am stronger because of it.  it took me a long time to learn and understand that. it took therapy and a shit ton of yoga, and different healing practices and it took getting sober. it also ruined countless relationships, jobs, opportunities, because i was just in so much pain and felt so incredibly alone and lost and responsible. and i realize how easily those feelings can get triggered.  i tell myself iâ€™m not attached to those feelings but hereâ€™s the deal. sometimes i just feel fucking lonely. sometimes all i want is someone to wrap their arms around me and say, â€œyou got this.â€ i hope i continue to connect with all of you out there, to help heal others in the ways i know how, and to continue to do what i love. i know thatâ€™s why iâ€™m here. and now iâ€™m ready and i give myself permission to be myself and tell you my stories.  because helping others and creating a space for you to heal, also creates a space for me to heal as well.

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
when the outside is pristine and the inside is a mess, and the pieces finally start to find their places. when all that remains of your pain is a dark spot on your heart that resembles the edges of blackened and burnt paper. when you see those jagged edges for the beauty they've etched into your face, and the words no longer rage with fury as they leave your mouth.
.
.
.
.
